                                <h4 class="ms-1 mb-1">3.1 Data Confidentiality Protocols</h4>
                                <p>We implement comprehensive confidentiality measures:</p>
                                <ul class="list-unstyled">
                                    <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                        <i class="fas fa-circle me-2"></i>End-to-end encryption for sensitive data: Our commitment to users goes beyond the usual, here communications (messaging) are encrypted and only end users have access.
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                        <i class="fas fa-circle me-2"></i>Role-based access control (RBAC): Roles can have sub-levels (for example, "Global Administrator" and "Local Administrator"); granular roles can also be implemented:
                                        <ul class="list-unstyled">
                                            <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                                <i class="fa-regular fa-circle me-1"></i>By module: A user can have access to only "Sales", but not to "Finance".
                                            </li>
                                            <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                                <i class="fa-regular fa-circle me-1"></i>By action: A user can view data but not modify it, or download a file but not delete it.
                                            </li>
                                            <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                                <i class="fa-regular fa-circle me-1"></i>By UI component: Access can be restricted to specific buttons, forms, or reports within a screen.
                                            </li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                        <i class="fas fa-circle me-2"></i>Multi-factor authentication (MFA): MFA is an authentication process where the user must provide more than one form of identification to access the system. This usually involves something like an additional verification code via email, text message/whatsapp, a fingerprint or facial recognition in cases where the user indicates that they want it.
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                        <i class="fas fa-circle me-2"></i>Session management and timeout controls: Session management involves controlling the length of time a user is active within a system. Timeout controls specify how long a session can be inactive before the system automatically logs it out. We have considered that the user must decide this, including unlimited time sessions, down to 15 minute sessions.
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                        <i class="fas fa-circle me-2"></i>Data access logging and monitoring: Data access logging and monitoring involves creating detailed logs of every action performed on the data, such as who accessed it, when, and what data was viewed or modified. In addition, constant monitoring allows suspicious or unauthorized activity to be detected in real time.
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="ms-2 me-2">
                                        <i class="fas fa-circle me-2"></i>Confidentiality agreements for all system users: Confidentiality agreements are legal contracts that ensure that employees, contractors, and other system users understand and agree to maintain the privacy of the data they access. These agreements typically define responsibilities and the legal consequences of violating confidentiality. We believe that institutions should regulate this; each user should agree to the confidentiality agreements of the institutions in which they participate.
                                    </li>
                                </ul>

